How can I fix this Java code to avoid a ConcurrentModificationException when iterating over a list and removing some elements? "import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        for (Integer n : numbers) {
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                numbers.remove(n);
            }
        }

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}"

answer:
You can't remove items from a list while iterating over it, because you are removing elements at the same index as the one you are iterating over. You can use an alternative approach by creating a copy of the list and then remove the elements:

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        List<Integer> copyNumbers = new ArrayList<>(numbers);
        for (Integer n : copyNumbers) {
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                numbers.remove(n);
            }
        }

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}

The output of this program would be: [2, 3, 5]

